[2] Brazil, vaccine adverse events
Date: Fri 29 Feb 2008
From: Seligman, Stephen
<stephen_seligman@nymc.edu>


Comment on "Adverse events associated with the YF
vaccine" posted on 25 Feb 2008 (20080228.0810).

The report from the Ministerio da Saude,
Secretaria de Vigilancia em Saude in Brazil
discusses adverse events associated with the YF
vaccine. Ambiguities in the report are most
likely related to the fact that investigation is
ongoing. Of 7 cases, one has been confirmed as a
fatal case of viscerotropic disease (YEL-AVD) and
6 others are currently considered as systemic
reactions to the vaccine, possibly linked to a
vaccine component, resulting in death.

In the past some cases thought to be yellow fever
have turned out to be vaccine related fever on
sequencing of the virus (1). On the other hand
some cases attributed to the vaccine were
secondary to wild-type virus (2). The age and sex
of YEL-AVD are of particular interest. It appears
that in cases under the age of 30, for unknown
reasons, most are in women in their 20s.

References
----------
(1). Vasconcelos PF, Bryant JE, da Rosa TP, Tesh
RB, Rodrigues SG, Barrett AD: Genetic divergence
and dispersal of yellow fever virus, Brazil.
Emerg Infect Dis 2004, 10:1578-1584
(2). Galler R, Pugachev KV, Santos CL, Ocran SW,
Jabor AV, Rodrigues SG, Marchevsky RS, Freire MS,
Almeida LF, Cruz AC, Yamamura AM, Rocco IM, da
Rosa ES, Souza LT, Vasconcelos PF, Guirakhoo F,
Monath TP: Phenotypic and molecular analyses of
yellow fever 17DD vaccine viruses associated with
serious adverse events in Brazil. Virology 2001,
290:309-319.

--
Stephen J. Seligman, M.D.
Research Professor
Department of Microbiology and Immunology
New York Medical College
Valhalla, NY 10595
<stephen_seligman@nymc.edu>

